[M. Zeb Hunter]

Course Project: A Model Comparison of Forecasting Hourly Real-Time Wholesale Power Prices at SPP North Hub

Problem Statement:

Electricity price forecasting is a heavily-studied subject in quantitative finance within the energy industry. Rafal Weron published a paper in the International Journal of Forecasting 30 (2014) 1030-1081 "Electricity price forecasting: A review of the state-of-the-art with a look into the future" describing the strengths and weaknesses of commonly used modelling techniques, ranging from jump-diffusion models, Markov regime switching models, statistical models (regression, AR-type, ARX-type, GARCH-type), and computational intelligence models (including support vector machines, decision trees, feedforward artificial neural networks and recurrent neural networks).

Weron's concludes his assessment of different NN computational models by stating...

"The pool of available CI (computational intelligence) tools is so diverse and rich that it is hard to find an optimal solution. Worse still, it is hard to compare the different CI methods thoroughly. Even if the forecasting accuracy is reported for the same market and the same out-of-sample (forecasting) test period, the errors of the individual methods are not truly comparable unless identical in-sample (calibration) periods are used as well, and therefore they cannot be used to formulate general statements about a method's efficiency unless such is the case."

After describing the broad range of electricity price forecasting techniques, Weron summarizes his conclusions as ...

"All of this calls for a comprehensive, thorough study involving (i) the same datasets, (ii) the same robust evaluation procedures, and (iii) statistical testing of the significance of one model's outperformance of another". (Weron p.1073)

The purpose of this project is to compare the performance of two different computational intelligence (neural network) models, as well as a timeseries benchmark model, on the same in-sample and out-of-sample dataset using robust empirical procedures for evaluating the significance of modelling performance.

In this project, I will focus on a comparison of the following three forecasting models:

  • Benchmark models (3): Regression, AR model, Multiple Seasonality TBATS
  • Extra Trees Regressor
  • Random Forest Regressor
  • Artificial Neural Network

Compare the Root Mean Squared Error on out-of-sample data in each model and determine if there is empirical evidence to support the significant outperformance of one model over the others.

To properly answer such a question I will try each Neural Network algorithm with a range of values of its parameters, determine the best fitting parameters of each model, and assess the statistical significance of the forecasting errors between the models.

Statistical Significance in Forecast Errors between Models:

In addition to comparing the RMSE on the test set between the models, I perform a student's t-test on the test set prediction errors between the best models of each type, and check p-values < .05 for statistically significant differences in the forecast errors.

Dataset Features & Response Variable:

This project is a comparison of regression models which predict the hourly wholesale electricity price at Southwest Power Pools Real Time "SPP North Hub" LMP. This represents the "Y" response variable, which may also be referred as "Power Price" throughout this report.

The complete raw dataset contains 24,900 observations of hours spanning July 21st, 2017 (Hour Ending 11) through May 26th 2020 Hour Ending 24. Each observation represents one hourly interval.

Background on Power Price Formulation:

The real-time electricity market in SPP solves for the lowest marginal price required to serve every Mega-watt ("MW" a unit of energy flow expressed over a period of time, e.g. each hour yields a MWh unit of total system demand for electricity) of Demand (aka "Load") subject to constraints on the transmission lines of the system.

Each generator offers to produce energy at a bid price in each hour, and SPP (the overall grid operator) aggregates the generation stack from cheapest unit to most expensive units. The grid operator determines the load requirement from all users of the system each hour, and directs all lowest-cost generators to run up until the system has generated all the required demand load. The generator serving the last MW of required load will set the market clearing price for all generators, effectively the system-wide energy price.

def reset_session(seed=42):
    tf.random.set_seed(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
    
def ts_split(ts, feature_steps=5*24, target_steps=1):
    n_obs = len(ts) - feature_steps - target_steps + 1
    X = np.array([ts[idx:idx + feature_steps] for idx in range(n_obs)])
    y = np.array([ts[idx + feature_steps:idx + feature_steps + target_steps]
                  for idx in range(n_obs)])
    return X, y

## Read data
data = pd.read_csv("SPP_HourlyData_2017_v3.csv")

The features in this dataset include hourly observations for each of the following variables:

HOURLY DATA

  • Time (categorical variables converted to onehotencoders)

    • Month
    • Hour Ending
    • Day of week

  • Load (demand) real-time

  • Generation quantities in total across SPP by fuel type in real-time

    • Wind, natural gas, coal, hydro, solar, nuclear

  • Total generation unit capacity on outage by fuel type in real time

    • Wind, natural gas, coal, hydro, solar, nuclear

  • Actual observed temperatures, wind speeds, cloud coverage

    • 3 locations each

  • Wind speeds

    • 3 locations

  • Hourly differences in each variable above

DAILY DATA - copied for every hour in each day

  • Daily natural gas spot prices

    • 3 locations each

  • Coal prices (prompt month futures price)

    • 3 locations

  • Total installed generation capacity in SPP by fuel type, aggregated by plant heat rate (plant efficiency rating)

    • Less variability each day, but changes over the years

Additional Features

  • The prior five days of hourly price changes are added to the data set for use in the AR Regression model

## Add features for the 120 prior hourly price values from the Price (response) variable
y_features_all_lm = pd.DataFrame(y_features_all_lm)
strs = ["y"+str(x) for x in range(periods_back)]
y_features_all_lm.columns = strs

v1 = X_all[periods_back:]
v1.columns = X_all.columns

v2 = y_features_all_lm
v2.columns = strs

v3 = y_all[periods_back:]

v1.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
v2.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
v3.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

# Merge X_all and hourly changes in Price
X_all_AR = pd.concat([v1, v2], axis=1, join='inner', ignore_index=True)
X_all_AR.columns = list(X_all.columns.T) + strs
y_all = v3

# Align index from original data after removing starting periods
index_all = data['DATETIME'][periods_back:]

## Transform Categorical variables to OneHotEncoder 
cat_attribs = ['MONTH','HOURENDING', 'DAYOFWEEK']
X_all_num = X_all_AR.drop(cat_attribs, axis=1)
X_all_cat = X_all_AR[cat_attribs]
num_attribs = list(X_all_num)

num_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('std_scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ])

full_pipeline = ColumnTransformer([
        ("num", num_pipeline, num_attribs),   
        ("cat", OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs),
    ])
In [213]:
## Separate training set on first 70% of data, validation on 20%, test on last 10%
n = X_all_AR.shape[0]
train_len = n*.75
val_len = n*.15
test_len = n*.1

# hourly Data 
val_start = int(round(train_len))
val_end = val_start + int(round(val_len))

index_train = index_all[:(val_start-1)].values
index_val  = index_all[val_start:val_end].values
index_test = index_all[(val_end+1):].values

## Subset data sets, 70% in training, 10% in validation, 20% in testing
X_train_raw = X_all_AR[:(val_start-1)]
X_val_raw  = X_all_AR[val_start:val_end]
X_test_raw = X_all_AR[(val_end+1):]

## Transform features with fit_transform on training set and transform on val/test feature set
X_train = pd.DataFrame(data=full_pipeline.fit_transform(X_train_raw))
X_val = pd.DataFrame(data=full_pipeline.transform(X_val_raw))
X_test = pd.DataFrame(data=full_pipeline.transform(X_test_raw))

y_train = pd.DataFrame(data=y_all[:(val_start-1)])
y_val  = pd.DataFrame(data=y_all[val_start:val_end])
y_test = pd.DataFrame(data=y_all[(val_end+1):])

X_train.index = index_train
X_val.index = index_val
X_test.index = index_test

y_train.index = index_train
y_val.index = index_val
y_test.index = index_test

Benchmark Model #1¶

First we evaluate a few benchmark models, starting with a linear regression model based on categorical variables HOURENDING, MONTH and DAYOFWEEK only.

Benchmark Model: Linear Model with autoregressive features

In [217]:
## Re-create one hot encoder variables for HOURENDING, MONTH and DAYOFWEEK

## Benchmark regression model
## Regression model using 1 layer ANN    
reset_session()

    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=[cat_col]),
    keras.layers.Dense(1)
])

                validation_data=(X_val_cat_1hot.values, y_val.values),
                callbacks=[checkpoint_cb, early_stopping_cb])

Extra Trees Regression Model¶

Next we develop an Extra Trees Regression model and use randomized grid search to hypertune the n_estimators and max_features parameters. 3 fold cross validation is performed with RMSE as the scoring metric.

In [239]:
## Extra Trees Model
param_distribs = {
        'n_estimators': randint(low=1, high=200),
        'max_features': randint(low=1, high=16),
    }

extraforest = ExtraTreesRegressor(bootstrap=True,oob_score=True,n_jobs=-1, random_state=42)

## Randomized Search on ExtraTrees hyperparameters
rnd_search = RandomizedSearchCV(extraforest, param_distributions=param_distribs, n_iter=10, cv=3, 
                          scoring='neg_root_mean_squared_error', random_state=42)

## Run randomized search
rnd_search.fit(X_train.values, y_train.values)

rmse_val_RF = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val, RF_preds_val['RF_Prediction'].values))
RF_preds_val['RF_error'] = RF_preds_val['RF_Prediction'] - RF_preds_val['y_val']

bins = np.linspace(-100, 200, 100)
pyplot.hist(RF_preds_val['RF_error'], bins, alpha=0.5, label='RF Errors')
pyplot.legend(loc='upper right')
pyplot.show()

## Plot the histogram of validation set errors
print("Random Forest Model: 10-Fold CV average training rmse score: {:.4f}, validation score: {:.4f}"
      .format(-cv_scores_RF.mean(), rmse_val_RF))
print("Validation Set Mean error for Random Forest Model: %.3f" % np.mean(RF_preds_val['RF_error']))

Validation Set Mean error for Random Forest Model: 3.143

ANN Model Prediction¶

In [288]:
feature_num = X_train.shape[1]

def MSE(y_true,y_pred):
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
    return mse

# Function to create model, required for KerasRegressor
def new_model(batch_norm = False, dropout=False, dropout_rate=0.2, 
              l = .0001, b1 = 0.9, b2 = 0.999, 
              layers = 5, neurons = 50,
              activation = ["elu"],
              initializer = ["he_normal"],
              optimizer="Adam"):
    
    if activation == "selu":
        initializer = "lecun_normal"
    
    if activation == "relu":
        initializer = "he_normal"
        
    if activation == "elu":
        initializer = "he_normal"
    
    # build new model
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    model.add(keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=[feature_num]))
    
    if batch_norm == True:
        keras.layers.BatchNormalization()
    
    if dropout == True:
        model.add(keras.layers.Dropout(rate=dropout_rate))
    
    for layer in range(layers):
        model.add(keras.layers.Dense(neurons, activation = activation, kernel_initializer = initializer))
        
        if batch_norm == True:
            keras.layers.BatchNormalization()
            
        if dropout == True:
            model.add(keras.layers.Dropout(rate=dropout_rate))
        
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1))
    
    if optimizer == "Adam":
        optimizer = keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=l, beta_1=b1, beta_2=b2)
    
    if optimizer == "SGD":
        optimizer = keras.optimizers.SGD(lr=0.01, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True, decay=1e-4)
    
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss="mse", optimizer=optimizer, metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()])
    
    return model

                  l = l, b1 = b1, b2 = b2, 
                  layers = layers, neurons = neurons,
                  activation = activation,
                  optimizer = optimizer)

# Save best model fit only
checkpoint_cb = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("best_ANN_06-08.h5",
                                                save_best_only=True)
# Stop early
early_stopping_cb = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=10,
                                                  min_delta=0.001,
                                                  restore_best_weights=True)

# Performance scheduling learning rate
lr_scheduler = keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(factor=0.5, patience=5)

## hypertune parameters with grid search
import time
start = time.time()

grid_result = grid.fit(X_train.values, y_train.values, epochs=10,
                       validation_data=(X_val.values, y_val.values), 
                       callbacks=[checkpoint_cb, early_stopping_cb, lr_scheduler])
end = time.time()

CONCLUSION:

Of all models, the ANN model has the best RMSE score in both the validation and test data sets.

The ANN model does have statistical significance in better mean forecasting error than the MSTS time series model, Categorical Regression, as well as the Random Forest and Extra Trees models. It's noteworthy that the AR linear regression model did have a lower mean error on the test set than the ANN model, and seems to better remove the average bias, however it does not have a lower RMSE than the ANN.

This provides evidence that the ANN model appears to be a better performing forecasting model for this problem statement than decision tree regressors and timeseries/regression models.

A final note...It's noteworthy that the test set RMSEs are all lower than the validation set RMSEs for each model. One reason may be that there are fewer instances of high prices in the testing set than the training or validation sets. Stratified sampling could have improved this however I wanted to preserve the timeseries nature of the dataset. Also, it was difficult to use the timeseriessplit function for cross validation as some of the models are not treated as a timeseries but rather independent features (Extra Trees, Random Forest and ANN).
